{
  "texts": [
    "1 3 Generative models: Exploring relationships and application environmentGenerative Adversarial Networks (GANs), Variational Autoencoders (VAEs), Flow-Based Models, and Diffusion Models are all different types of generative models, each with their own set of strengths and weaknesses.Due to their complimentary nature, GANs and VAEs have been widely investigated together.",
    "GANs use adversarial training to encourage realistic sample production, whereas VAEs provide a probabilistic framework for encoding and decoding latent representations.",
    "Notable publications, such as \"Auto-Encoding Variational Bayes\" by Kingma and Welling (2013) and \"Generative Adversarial Nets\" by Goodfellow et al. (2014), have helped to create linkages between these two fundamental techniques.",
    "Furthermore, the relationship between GANs and flow-based models is explored in works such as \"Density Estimation using Real NVP\" by Dinh et al. (2017), which examines the potential synergy between Gans' implicit generative capabilities and flow-based models' explicit density estimation methods.",
    "The intersection with Diffusion Models, as proven by Gulrajani et al. (2017)'s \"Improved Training of Wasserstein GANs,\" adds to our understanding of generative modeling by including the diffusion process as an alternative to conventional sampling strategies.Investigating these links gives a full perspective of the generative modeling landscape and paves the way for hybrid models that combine the characteristics of each technique to improve overall performance and reliability."
  ]
}